re, England":"Whitby, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Blankney, Lincolnshire, England":"Blankney, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1176–about 20 July 1293":"1176–about 20 July 1293","1225–1257":"1225–1257","1170–1244":"1170–from8January1244to7January1245","1242–Male":"1242–Deceased","1250–1327":"1250–1327","1176–1293":"1176–1293","before 1242":"before 1242","1176":"1176","1242":"1242","about 20 July 1293":"about 20 July 1293","after 20 July 1293":"after 20 July 1293","1250":"1250","1293":"1293","14 October 1257":"14 October 1257","1170":"1170","1327":"1327","Abt 1250":"about 1250","1225":"1225","Abt 1245":"about 1245","1257":"1257","1244":"from 8 January 1244 to 7 January 1245","about 1242":"about 1242","Topcliffe, North Yorkshire, England":"Topcliffe, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Whitby, Scarborough, Yorkshire, England":"Whitby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Blankney, Lincolnshire, England":"Blankney, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Neville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Neuville in Calvados or Néville in Seine-Maritime, both so called from Old French <i>neu(f)</i> ‘new’ (from Latin <i>novus</i>) + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. One family line, originally from Neuville (Calvados), became powerful during the Wars of the Roses through Richard <i>Neville</i> (1428–71), 16th Earl of Warwick, nicknamed \"The Kingmaker\".","Irish (Munster): assimilation of the Gaelic name <b>Ó Niadh</b> (see   Nee  ) and sometimes of <b>Ó Cnaimhín</b> (see   Nevin  ).","History: George Neville came to VA in or <i>c.</i> 1700 and settled on the headwaters of the Occoquan River, acquiring a large estate. His descendants, bearing the surnames Neville and Craig, were of considerable importance in Pittsburgh, PA, and Cincinnati, OH."],"variants":[{"name":"Nevells","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevils","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Novel","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  .","Catalan: variant of   Novell  ."]},{"name":"Newell","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  .","English: variant of   Noel  .","English: variant of   Newhall  ."]},{"name":"Nevills","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Nevil","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Newill","meanings":["English and Irish (or Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevill","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevels","meanings":["English and Scottish (Wigtownshire): of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain.","Dutch and North German: unexplained."]},{"name":"Nee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, John Patrick.","Irish (Galway): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Niadh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Nia</i>’ or <b>Mac Niadh</b> ‘son of <i>Nia</i>’. Compare   McNee  .   Needham   2 and   Neville   have also been adopted as Anglicized forms of this name.","North German: possibly a relationship name from Middle Low German <i>neve</i> ‘nephew, grand-child’."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Neville was born in 1176, in Topcliffe, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Richard de Percy before 1242. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died about 20 July 1293, in Blankney, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 117, and was buried in Whitby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1176–about 20 July 1293":"1176–umbes 20. juuli 1293","1225–1257":"1225–1257","1170–1244":"1170–8.jaanuar1244kuni7.jaanuar1245","1242–Male":"1242–Surnud","1250–1327":"1250–1327","1176–1293":"1176–1293","before 1242":"enne 1242","1176":"1176","1242":"1242","about 20 July 1293":"umbes 20. juuli 1293","after 20 July 1293":"pärast 20. juulit 1293","1250":"1250","1293":"1293","14 October 1257":"14. oktoober 1257","1170":"1170","1327":"1327","Abt 1250":"umbes 1250","1225":"1225","Abt 1245":"umbes 1245","1257":"1257","1244":"8. jaanuar 1244 kuni 7. jaanuar 1245","about 1242":"umbes 1242","Topcliffe, North Yorkshire, England":"Topcliffe, North Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Whitby, Scarborough, Yorkshire, England":"Whitby, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Blankney, Lincolnshire, England":"Blankney, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1176–about 20 July 1293":"1176–noin 20. heinäkuuta 1293","1225–1257":"1225–1257","1170–1244":"1170–vuodesta8.tammikuuta1244vuoteen7.tammikuuta1245","1242–Male":"1242–Kuollut","1250–1327":"1250–1327","1176–1293":"1176–1293","before 1242":"ennen vuotta 1242","1176":"1176","1242":"1242","about 20 July 1293":"noin 20. heinäkuuta 1293","after 20 July 1293":"20. heinäkuuta 1293 jäl